(fifthQuint)Imaging Study of 3D-CBCT Sialography and MRI Sialography in Non Tumor Salivary Diseases.

 Our study focuses on patients over 18 years, with unilateral or bilateral parotid or submandibular salivary symptoms.

 Each patient included is given a MRI sialography and a 3D-CBCT sialography at a later stage when the acute episode has subsided.

 Images are archived on the Carestream Picture Archiving Communication System (PACS).

 Interpretation is achieved after Multi-Planar Reconstruction (MPR), Maximal Intensity Projection (MIP) and three-dimensional rendering.

 A primary radiological analysis of the two procedures is systematically done by a specialist radiologist for the diagnostic and therapeutic care of the patient.

 A second radiological data analysis is carried out at the end of the study, by a specialized radiologist, different from the first one, to asses the two radiological examinations.

 The primary outcome measure is the capability of the radiological technique to detect a ductal salivary feature.

 Secondary outcomes include the clinical characteristics of the patients, the diagnostic capabilities in identifying the salivary lesions, their number, their precise location and measurements.

 A primary side effect in catheterization and dosimetric parameters for the CBCT technique will be systematically recorded.

